commit_message: Initial commit to vcr.
Added FakeWeb.remove_from_registry method so we can remove specific registrations.
Added basic sandbox api to VCR module:- #create_sandbox!n- #destroy_sandbox!n- #current_sandboxn- #with_sandbox
Added VCR::RecordedResponse struct.
Hooked into Net::HTTP#request so that the response gets stored in the correct current_sandbox.
Added logic to sandbox to make it set and restore FakeWeb.allow_net_connect properly.
Added logic to VCR::Config.cache_dir= so that it creates the cache dir if it doesn't exist.
Write recorded responses to disk when the sandbox is destroyed.
Load the recorded responses from the cached yml file when the sandbox is created.
Register the recorded responses with fakeweb when the sandbox is created.
Use record mode to determine if we should register the recorded responses with fakeweb.
De-register the fakeweb responses when the sandbox is destroyed.
Ensure that we don't write previously recorded responses to disk if there are no new ones.
Added a #cache_file method to sandbox that takes care of ensuring the filename is valid.
Added default_sandbox_record_mode config setting.  Updated the record_mode logic so we ensure we have a valid value.
Ensure that @original_recorded_responses and @recorded_responses are separate array instances, so that #new_recorded_responses works properly.
Allow sandbox cache_file names to have path separators.
Added the VCR.config method that yields the config object.  This supports the nice VCR.config do |c| .... end syntax.
Create the cache file subdirectory if it doesn't exist before trying to write to it.
Added cucumber tagging support.
Added cucumber features.
Updated gemfile settings in rakefile.
Added defined?(Jeweler) check so that rake spec can be run without jeweler being installed.This is needed for runcoderun to be able to run the specs.
Added gem dependency to fakeweb.
Require rubygems in spec_helper.rb.  This is needed in order to run the specs on ruby 1.8.x.
String#start_with? is a handy method, but it's not available in Ruby 1.8.6.  Use a regex instead so it works on ruby 1.8.6, 1.8.7 and 1.9.1.
Added code to start the debugger if it's available when running our specs or features.

Apparently different versions of ruby dump yaml differently (I didn't know that before).  The yaml files I dumped while running ruby 1.9.1 don't work when running the specs under 1.8.6.To fix this, I've split up the yaml fixtures into separate directories for each ruby version.
Ensure we are creating our sandboxes with a valid record mode.
Updated the default rake task to run specs and features.
Set a default record mode in the vcr spec so each individual spec doesn't have to set it.
Renamed sandbox to cassette since cassette fits with our VCR metaphor better.
Set the global settings in before/after blocks to allow specs to pass.  I guess these settings were set by luck before, because I wasn't getting the failures I'm getting now.
Updated the spec messages to not use should for each message.  It's unnecessary noise.
Fixed our .gitignore to ignore temp fixtures.
Updated the readme.
Version bump to 0.1.0
Handle asynchronous HTTP requests (such as for mechanize).  This resolves GH issue 1.
Version bump to 0.1.1
Adding gemspec.
Regenerated gemspec for version 0.1.1
Moved all of the extensions into their own folder.
Updated README.
Fixed spec name.
Removed temp fixture file that I accidentally committed.

Fixed our Net::HTTP monkey patch so that it only stores a the recorded response once per request.  Internally, Net::HTTP#request recursively calls itself (passing slightly different arguments) in certain circumstances.
Got things to work for when a cassette records multiple requests made to the same URL with the same HTTP verb, but different responses.  We have to register an array of responses with fakeweb.
Added explanatory note about VCR to FakeWeb::NetConnectNotAllowedError#message.
Added history.rdoc.
Version bump to 0.1.2
Regenerated gemspec.
Changed the configuration option to have a default_cassette_options hash. #default_cassette_record_mode is deprecated.
Added a global before/after that sets default settings for VCR and fakeweb, so our specs don't have to keep setting things back to the defaults in their own before and after blocks.
Added #allow_real_http cassette option, that allows real http requests for URLs that return true for the given lambda.
Updated readme.
Updated the history.
Version bump to 0.2.0
Updated gemspec.
Refactored some of the step definitions.
Added asynchronous request replay scenario.  This functionality works but I didn't a scenario demonstrating it before.
Corrected the wording on a couple of specs.
Fixed a typo and the copyright date.
Updated Readme with links to the CI servers.

Updated some of the method names/option keys to fit the VCR metaphor better.  The first pass of the code was based on sandboxes rather than cassettes and the terminology reflected that.Changes:nn* VCR.create_cassette! => VCR.insert_cassetten* VCR.destroy_cassette! => VCR.eject_cassetten* VCR.with_cassette => VCR.use_cassetten* VCR::Cassette#destroy! => VCR::Cassette#ejectn* VCR::Cassette#cache_file => VCR::Cassette#filen* VCR::Config.cache_dir => VCR::Config.cassette_library_dirn* :unregistered record mode => :new_episodes record moden
Moved the VCR::Config.default_cassette_record_mode deprecation into the deprecation file.
Updated readme.
Fixed deprecation warning message to use the correct method name.
0.3.0 release.
Updated our Net::HTTP extension so that the response is yielded after the response is stored, in case the block has a return statement.  Closes GH-1.
0.3.1 release.
Added request body and headers to recorded response.  These will come in handy for getting VCR to work with webmock.
Extracted the interactions with FakeWeb into an adapter so we can implement the same adapter interface for other http stubbing libraries like WebMock.
Pulled the fakeweb logic that constructs the request_uri out of the net http extension and put it in the fakeweb extension.
Use the fakeweb http_stubbing_adapter rather than using fakeweb directly.
Updated features rake task to run the features against multiple http_stubbing_adapters.
Instead of unstubbing the previously stubbed requests, use a checkpoint system, so that the http_stubbing registry is returned to exactly the same state.
Removed unneeded fakeweb extensions.

Changed the format of the cassettes.  Use a VCR structured object rather than a Net::HTTP response as that is tied directly to net/http and I hope to get this to work with other http libraries eventually.
Added rake task to migrate old VCR cassettes to the new format, to make it easy for VCR users to upgrade.
Migrated all of the vcr cassette fixtures using the rake task.
Added back request bodies since I had lost them in the migration.
Updated the code to work with the new structs and terminology.
Implemented the WebMock http stubbing adapter.

Updated the http interaction structs:- Renamed RequestSignature to Request since the object represents the actual request.n- Changed the response headers to use an array for the values, since a response can have multiple values for the same header.
Updated our cassette fixtures to the latest format.
Use VCR.http_stubbing_adapter rather than VCR::Config.http_stubbing_adapter.
Allow the webmock adapter to be used.
Update the default rake task to that it runs the features with the webmock adapter in addition to the fakeweb one.
Temporarily disable a spec that won't pass until some changes are made to webmock.
Load our net/http extension so it gets used when webmock is used.  When fakeweb is used, our net/http extension has to be loaded after it, so we load it after webmock as well.
Simplified our net http extension.
Added logic to VCR::Config.http_stubbing_adapter so that it returns the appropriate value if just one of fakeweb/webmock are loaded.
Raise a helpful error message when people try to use VCR with deprecated cassettes.
Made most of VCR::Cassette's methods private.  I had forgotten to make the methods private before, but most of them don't need to be exposed.
Reorganized some code.
Disallow http connections by default.
Updated exception message to be more helpful.
Check that the versions of FakeWeb and WebMock are supported.

Disallow http connections and check the adapter version when the VCR.config block completes, rather than the first time http_stubbing_adpater is accessed.  This ensures that these things are done before the test suite starts running.
Bumped the webmock version requirement to 1.1.0 as that is the version number that will be used for the webmock release that supports VCR.
Override WebMock::NetConnectNotAllowedError so that it includes a helpful message about using VCR.
Added a benchmark to test the performance characterstics of fakeweb vs webmock.
Renamed file.
Fixed the vcr task so it actually, you know....works.
Change History file to markdown format and renamed it to changelog.
Renamed VCR::Cassette#http_stubbing_adapter to http_stubbing_library.
Changed the readme to markdown format, and re-wrote most of it.
Updated CHANGELOG with the info about what is coming in the next release.
Updated gemspec info.
Updated the cucumber VCR configuration so that it uses :fakeweb by default if HTTP_STUBBING_ADAPTER is not set.

Use strings instead of symbols for the hash keys for Net::HTTP.post_form.On my ruby 1.9.1 CI server, the build is failing with this error: TypeError: can't dup Symbol.  I can't repro this locally (maybe a different 1.9.1 patch level?), but I think this may fix it.
0.4.0 release.

Fixed a bug: Net::HTTPResponse#read_body was raising an error because VCR pre-read the body when recording a new request.My fix is to extend the already read response with a module that attempts to preserve the behavior of #read_body when the response has not yet been read.
0.4.1 release.

Removed dependency on jeweler.  Manage the gemspec by hand instead.  Exposed the version:- VCR.version tt=> string (in the format major.minor.patch)n- VCR.version.parts => array of integersn- VCR.version.major => integern- VCR.version.minor => integern- VCR.version.patch => integer
Use the version in the URL to the README.
Added cucumber scenario that demonstrates the use of a regex for a URI in a cassette.
Updated README with info about putting regexes in cassettes.

Remove the Net::ReadAdapter extension.  We don't need it now that we record the response before calling the block passed to Net::HTTP#request.  Our Net::HTTPResponse extension takes care of making the response act as if it's never been read and works with asynchronous requests properly.
Refactored the http_stubbing_adapter shared spec so that it can be re-used for the different http libraries that webmock supports.
Move the Net::HTTP-specific scenarios and cucumber steps into separate files, so the main feature/step files can be re-used for multiple http libraries.
Refactor the vcr steps so they are polymorphic, and can use whichever HTTP library is passed as HTTP_LIB.
Moved code out of fakeweb extension and into fakeweb http_stubbing_adapter.

Changed the way we allow requests to localhost: rather than having a per-cassette :allow_real_http option, use a #ignore_localhost config setting.There's no way to make the :allow_real_http option work for the other http libraries.  This is a simpler way to get the important functionality.
Fixed warning: already initialized constant NET_CONNECT_NOT_ALLOWED_ERROR.
Work around a bug in WebMock.
Ensure #request_stubbed? works, regardless of if the uri is a string or URI.
Refactored our Net::HTTP recording, and corresponding specs, to make it easier to setup the recording of WebMock's other http libraries, and have them share the same specs.
Remove old deprecations.  The next release will be VCR 1.0.0, indicating breaking changes.
Removed webmock work around that is no longer necessary.
Disable FakeWeb::VERSION constant reassignment warnings.
Hooked up recording of other http libraries, using WebMock.after_request callback.
Some slight refactoring of our extensions.WebMock has the same Net::HTTPResponse extension module I have, and to prevent instance variable name collisions, I renamed the instance variable I use.
Updated the fakeweb vs webmock benchmarks using the latest webmock.
Added cucumber scenarios to test using HTTPClient asynchronously.
Fixed some formatting.
Generalized a cucumber step so I can easily pass different options to a cassette.
Added :erb option that enables dynamic erb cassettes.
Configured rcov rake task.
Removed some unused code.
Honor default :erb option.
Raise a more helpful error message when the ERB in a cassette references an undefined variable.
Clarified spec name.

Ensure VCR.http_stubbing_adapter returns the adapter being tested.I guess this was happening by luck previously (allowing the specs to pass on my box) but the changed order of the specs on the CI server caused it to be a different adapter, causing some failing specs.
Added necessary before/after blocks to prevent WebMock from extending the response with WebMock's version of the same response extension.
Fixed the ignore_localhost option so that localhost requests are never recorded when it's set to true.
Kill the localserver processes when the test process exits.
Refactored rakefile so that we have features:fakeweb and features:webmock rake tasks.
Our specs that depend on the spawning of a localhost webserver in a separate process do not pass on heroku due to their restrictions, so I've disabled them here when the specs are run on heroku.
Fixed the heroku pending module so it passes the pending message to the pending method.
Disable cucumber scenarios that can't pass on heroku due to heroku's restrictions.
Don't set message expectations on nil.
Add capybara as an explicit development dependency since we use Capybara::Server to start a localhost server in some tests.
Ignore error that occurs occassionally when the child process exits immediately before #wait is called.
Fixed ignore_localhost so that localhost requests are not registered with the http_stubbing_adapter.
Added spec and feature coverage for em-http-request support.
Require webmock 1.3.0.
Added check_dependencies rake task that is a prerequesite for the specs and features.
Relax the cucumber version requirement a bit.
Updated benchmarks with latest results.
Use #ignore_localhost? rather than #ignore_localhost, since it's more idiomatic ruby.
Gracefully used requirement? or version_requirements? based on which is available.  It appears that requirement? isn't available in rubygems 1.3.5.
1.0.0 release.
Got specs and features to pass on jruby.
Improve the speed of some specs: rather than repeating the same HTTP request for each spec, make the HTTP request once, and then clone the response for each spec.
The code that stops the localhost server process isn't working on 1.9.2.Hopefully I can fix it at some point, but for now I'm disabling it and the code that depends on it for 1.9.2.n

Got the specs and features to pass on 1.9.2.Ruby 1.9.1 has some slight YAML serialization differences from 1.8.x.  1.9.2 has the same YAML serialization as 1.8.x, so I've changed the fixtures directories from 1.8.6, 1.8.7 and 1.9.1 to 1.9.1 and not_1.9.1.n
Add 1.9.2-preview3 to the list of tested ruby versions.

Fixed localhost server so that it properly shuts down with rack 1.2.1.I had disabled this for 1.9.2 because I thought it was an issue with that version of ruby, but it was actually an issue with having rack 1.2.1 installed for 1.9.2.  Now I've re-enabled it for 1.9.2.
Ignore rubinius .rbc files.
Fixed readme--the :erb setting should be true rather than :true (a symbol).
Added tags to .gitignore.
Fixed requires so that each spec file can be run individually.

Normalize request and response headers so they are always saved with lower case keys and arrays of values.This is the way Net::HTTP normalizes them, but recording non-Net::HTTPnrequests resulted in cassettes with headers that deviated from thisnnorm.
Fixed VCR.use_cassette so that it only ejects the cassette if it was successfully inserted.
Added spec for basic auth for #request_uri on the http stubbing adapters.
Fixed an undefined constant FakeWeb::Utility error
Fixed spec description.
Reorganized specs so that they are grouped more logically.
Updated README.
1.0.1 release.
Use the --debugger option rather than starting the debugger manually.
Use bundler to manage gem dependencies.
Silence WEBrick logging.
Disable the --debugger option for jruby since ruby-debug can't be installed on jruby.
The current version of rack (1.2.1) does not work on ruby 1.8.6, so lock the dependency to 1.2.0.
Ensure the response body is serialized as a raw string, without any extensions on the string instance.This is needed for rest-client.  Closes #4.
Add conditional check so we don't get an exception for a nil body.
Removed check_dependencies rake task.  It's no longer necessary with bundler.
1.0.2 release.
Use the platform feature of bundler rather than conditional checks.Commit the Gemfile.lock file to lock us to this set of gems.
Lock cucumber to 0.8.5 or greater.  Added rake as a development dependency since I use it for development.
Added a be_tagged_with matcher since cucumber no longer provides the #tagged_with? method.
Lock to em-http-request 0.2.7.The newest release (0.2.10) doesn't work with webmock--see http://github.com/bblimke/webmock/issues/issue/29 for more info.
Upgrade to rspec-2.
Added spec focused filtering.
Use cucumber Around hook rather than Before/After hooks, as it simplifies the code significantly.
Simplify passing the block to VCR.use_cassette -- use &block rather than { block.call }.

Require WebMock 1.3.3 or greater.Previous versions did not handle multiple values for the same response header correctly.  Note that FakeWeb has this issue, too, and I've submitted a patch to fix it.nnThis closes issue #7.
Added link to the new google group.
Updated README section about WebMock and FakeWeb.
Updated VCR usage suggestions.
Added note about other similar libraries to the README.
Updated README to mention RSpec 2 usage.
1.0.3 release.
Updated Gemfile.lock.
Removed task runner as it's no longer needed.
Raise an error if VCR::Cassette.new is given invalid options.
Optimized ERB rendering a bit.
Updated em-http-request to 0.2.10.See http://github.com/igrigorik/em-http-request/issues/42 for more info about some of the changes.
Extracted the http calls from the specs for each http library into modules that we can use in our cucumber features to keep things DRY.
Updated URLs in our cucumber scenarios to be full URLs.URI.parse('http://example.com') raises an error because it lacks a path.nURI.parse('http://example.com/') does not ('/' is the path).
Ignore .bundle dir.
Simplify Net::HTTP extension a bit.
Enable debugger in specs.
Added some failing scenarios for the new :match_requests_on feature I'm working on.
Added RequestMatcher, which we'll use to determine which parts of an HTTP request to match on.
Added VCR::Request#matcher, which returns a request matcher for the given request, using the provided match_attributes.
Changed the HTTP Stubbing Adapters to support the match_requests_on option.
Documentation updates for new :match_requests_on option.
Minor documentation tweaks.
Added failing spec to show a problem with recording request headers before the real request is made.
Do not record Net::HTTP request headers that it defaults late in the http request process.Closes #10.
Simplified implementation of RequestMatcher#hash.
Fixed RequestMatcher to handle regex URIs.
Updated README to recommend putting the vcr cassette library directory outside of test/fixtures for a Rails 3 app.This closes #9.
Updated Gemfile to use rspec-core off of github since I'm using some features that haven't been released in a gem yet.
Disable rspec debug for java since ruby-debug doesn't install cleanly on jruby with bundler.
Updated http_stubbing_adapter.request_stubbed? so that it uses a RequestMatcher.
Refactored some tests.
Fixed some host specs to include a path.
Add support for matching requests on :path.
Use the latest rspec-expectations from github since it includes a 1.8.6 compatibility fix that hasn't been released yet.
Fix specs so they pass on 1.8.6.
1.9.2 compatibility fix: sort attributes before putting them in a Set.On 1.9.2, Set.new([1, 2]).hash != Set.new([2, 1]).hash, but Set.new([1, 2]).hash == Set.new([1, 2]).hash.

1.9.2 compatibility fix: don't try to use ruby-debug on 1.9.2.On 1.9.2, I'm getting errors like these:nndyld: lazy symbol binding failed: Symbol not found: _rb_method_noden  Referenced from: /Users/mmarston/.rvm/gems/ruby-1.9.2-p0/gems/ruby-debug-base19-0.11.23/lib/ruby_debug.bundlen  Expected in: flat namespacenndyld: Symbol not found: _rb_method_noden  Referenced from: /Users/mmarston/.rvm/gems/ruby-1.9.2-p0/gems/ruby-debug-base19-0.11.23/lib/ruby_debug.bundlen  Expected in: flat namespacen

1.9.2 compatibility fix: in an override, use an alias to refer to the original method rather than super.This works around an error I'm getting on 1.9.2:nnsuper from singleton method that is defined to multiple classes is not supported; this will be fixed in 1.9.3 or latern
Make it easy to temporarily use documentation format for the specs.

1.9.1 compatibility fix: moved a constant to the global namespace to avoid an rspec bug that manifests on 1.9.1.See these links for more info:n- http://github.com/rspec/rspec-core/issues#issue/41/comment/365562n- http://gist.github.com/543381
Lock rspec-core to one of my branches that fixes an issue with shared example groups on 1.8.6.
Require spec_helper's full expanded path so it's not loaded twice.
Fixed Gemfile so rbx can use it.  rcov doesn't work on rbx.
Readme updates.
1.1.0 release.
Removed default value of argument--there's no need for it.

Optimized #stub_requests a bit.Appending to an array with `<< value` is faster than with `+= [value]`, as it doesn't create a new array object for each append.nnA benchmark shows there is about a 10x performance difference:nnhttp://gist.github.com/544809
Upgrade to FakeWeb 1.3.0.
The latest FakeWeb passes this spec (was pending before).
Use FakeWeb::Utility.request_uri_as_string rather than our own logic to create the request uri.

Use a localhost regex with FakeWeb.allow_net_connect for the ignore_localhost feature.This is simpler than changing allow_net_connect from false to true and back again in our Net::HTTP extension for a localhost request.
Require FakeWeb 1.3.0 or greater.
Change http stubbing adapters to be modules rather than classes.They should never be instantiated and don't really hold state.  A module is more appropriate here.

Refactored and updated #check_version! on FakeWeb/WebMock adapters so that a warning is printed for a version with a greater major or minor version number.This simulates the ~> gem comparison operator, and is inspired by wycats' recent blog post:nnhttp://yehudakatz.com/2010/08/21/using-considered-harmful-or-whats-wrong-with/
Updated Gemfile/gemspec/Rakefile, etc to use latest best practices based on the gem skeleton that bundler generates.
Add missing test coverage for #ignore_localhost?
Lock dev dependency to WebMock 1.3.3.On 1.3.4 I get a failing cucumber scenario, but I believe it's a bug in WebMock.  I'm going to investigate more.
Add REE to list of tested ruby interpretters.
The newest ruby-debug-base19 isn't working on 1.9.1 for me, so lock to the previous release.
1.1.1 release.
List patron and em-http-request in our Gemfile so that our Gemfile.lock doesn't change everytime we run something on JRuby.
When the result of a request is an exception, raise it, rather than trying to read a body from it.
Update a few development gems.
Don't extend a Net::HTTP response with our module when WebMock has already extended it with its own module.These modules duplicate the same behavior and stomp on each other's toes.
Simplify implementation of VCR::Net::HTTPResponse.
Remove unnecessary cucumber LoadError rescue.
Add ability to disable Net::HTTP monkey patches for some specs.
Fix VCR::Net::HTTPResponse so it handles a nil body (such as for a HEAD request).
Documentation update.
1.1.2 release.
Update some gems.  Use rspec 2.0.0.beta.22 rather than locking to a specific git commit.
Improved the :all record mode so that it keeps previously recorded interactions that do not match the new recorded interactions.Previously, all of the previously recorded interactions were deleted.nn
Improve wording of some cucumber steps.
A few gemspec tweaks.
Added timecop so we can simulate the passage of time in our tests.
Add :re_record_interval cassette option.This option causes a cassette to be re-recorded when the existing file is older than the specified interval.
Don't auto re-record a cassette if there is no internet connection available.
Fix spec_helper requires.  spec is on the load path.
Add aruba for use in cucumber features.
Improved RSpec support.Added #use_vcr_cassette macro method that sets up a cassette for an example group.
Fix for ruby 1.9: ping was removed from the 1.9 standard library.
Updated to the latest rspec-core on github.

Fix WebMock/Net::HTTP integration.Rather than using a Net::HTTP monkey patch to record new requests, use WebMock's callback.  This prevents the monkey patches from colliding each other and ensures that VCR & WebMock work properly with Open URI.nnCloses #14.
Update changelog.
Use NameError#name rather than parsing the name from the message with a regex.
Don't use parallel assignment as it doesn't work in this case on rubinius.For more info, see this issue on the rubinius issue tracker:nnhttp://github.com/evanphx/rubinius/issues/502
Consider 0.0.0.0 to be a localhost alias.Note that WebMock doesn't yet consider 0.0.0.0 to be localhost, so it doesn't fully work if you use WebMock.nnCloses #15.

Add RSpec 1 as a submodule at vendor/rspec-1.I want to ensure the new RSpec macros work with RSpec 1, and this is the easiest way I can find to test it, since I can't add multiple versions of RSpec to my gemfile.n
Fixed RSpec `use_vcr_cassette` macro so that it works with RSpec 1.Closes #16.
Only require the Net::HTTPResponse extension where it is needed.We no longer needed it for WebMock, so there's no point in requiring when it's not needed.
Autoload vcr/cucumber_tags, rather than always requiring it.This is only needed for people using VCR with cucumber, so we shouldn't always require it.
Autoload 'vcr/rspec' when VCR::RSpec is referenced.That way, people can just require 'vcr' to use the new RSpec macros...but requiring 'vcr/rspec' works, too.
Autoload 'vcr/internet_connection' as it is only used sometimes and there's no need to always require it.
Remove some unnecessary code.
Add documentation about the new :re_record_interval option.
Add documentation about new RSpec macros.
Downgrade rack and remove capybara.
Rewrote localhost server so it doesn't depend on capybara.
Deal with weird load path issue on jruby.This fixes the rspec-1 scenario so that it passes on jruby.
Lock webmock to latest dev version on github.
Remove pending...the latest WebMock considers 0.0.0.0 to be localhost.
Add curb dependency.
Add test coverage for Curb support.
Update to rspec 2.0.0.rc.
README formatting.
Move some requires around so the reason for the ordering is more clear.
Fixed curb http adapter module so it supports all HTTP methods.
Don't run curb specs on jruby since jruby doesn't support curb.
Added a couple more similar libraries.
Update to rspec 2.0.0.
Add links to github comparison view for each release.
Update vendored rspec 1 to my fork that ignored rubinius .rbc files.
Got specs and features to pass on rubinius 1.1.
Update README.
Fixed typo.
Upgrade to WebMock 1.4.0.
1.2.0 release.
The documentation has moved to the wiki.
Finish sentence.
Remove unncessary should.
Remove methods of WebMock adapter that are no longer necessary.These were necessary when we used our Net::HTTP extension with WebMock.
Refactor addition of VCR info to exception message.
Specify that stubbing adapters should return rotate through multiple responses for the same request.
Move some code around so related methods are near each other.
Refactor to reduce duplication.
Update changelog.
Fix InternetConnection.available? so that it memoizes correctly when a connection is not available.
Update webmock to 1.5.0.
Allow newly released WebMock 1.5.0 to be used without a warning.
Fix spec docstring.
It's the wiki, not the README.
Setup guard-rspec.
Start TODO list.
Add typhoeus dependency.
Add Typhoeus adapter.
Deal with some edge cases that Typhoeus doesn't quite handle right yet.
Update typhoeus and fix remaining typhoeus specs.
Add MultiObjectProxy.Instances of this class proxy method calls to multiple objects, and will be useful to allow multiple http stubbing adapters to be used.n
Deprecate config.http_stubbing_library= in favor of config.stub_with.Use the MultiObjectProxy to allow multiple adapters to be used.n

For consistency, predicate methods should return a boolean.This is particularly important for our new MultiObjectProxy as it raises an error when the proxied objects return different values for predicat methods.n
Ensure FakeWeb adapter is used for Net::HTTP extension specs since FakeWeb is the only adapter that needs it.
Ensure header hash is recorded correctly.
Refactor header normalization specs a bit.
Ensure URIs are recorded in a normalized format.
Fix webmock dependency declaration to work on ruby 1.8.6.
Use Kernel.raise (needed for BasicObject on 1.9).
Don't bother using the MultiObjectProxy when there is only one adapter configured.There's no reason to add the additional overhead of the proxy if its not needed.
Fix Gemfile so it works on JRuby.
Upgrade to RSpec 2.1.
Allow specs to run on JRuby, which can't use Typhoeus.
Update typhoeus (latest fixes a bug on 1.8.6).
Setup cukes to run against typhoeus.
Add full_build script. Run ./full_build to run all specs/cukes against all supported rubies.
Add jruby-openssl gem for jruby.

Use Psych if it is available.Syck (the default YAML engine) modifies strings when they arenround-tripped through it: 1/n /n2 becomes 1/n/n2.  Psych doesn't.nnThis doesn't usually matter, but can occasionally cause problems whennusing an HTTP client that raises errors when the content_length headerndoes not match the actual content length (as does Mechanize).nnTo use psych, you may need to reinstall ruby 1.9.2 with psych support.nOn OSX with homebrew and rvm, this will do the trick:nnbrew install libyamlnrvm install ruby-1.9.2 --with-libyaml-dir=/usr/localnnFor more info, see the following:nn- https://gist.github.com/815769n- https://github.com/myronmarston/vcr/issues#issue/43n

Ensure that header values are the same when recording and replaying.- Typhoeus would have a single header value like 'text/html' when recording, but it was in an array on playback ['text/html'].n- Faraday headers are returned with lower case keys, and I was not handling this properly at all.nnThere are a few adapter/http library combinations that do not work properly when there are multiple values for one header:n- Faraday/Patronn- WebMock/HTTP Clientn- WebMock/EM HTTP Requestn- WebMock/CurbnnI think this is due to a bug in those libraries.  I could change the way I pass headers to Faraday and WebMock, but that would break the other libs used with Faraday and WebMock (i.e. Faraday/Net::HTTP or WebMock/Net::HTTP) so I think it's best for now to just leave these pending.nnCloses #50.

Add after_http_request hook.For issue #91.nnNote that when using Typhoeus or WebMock, it's not guaranteed that the after_request hook will fire for every request; if an error (such as a socket error) occurs before the request completes then the Typhoeus/WebMock after_request hook will not fire, which means VCR will not be able to fire its after_http_request hook in turn.  There's not much I can do about this, unfortunately.nnFor Excon, Faraday and FakeWeb, I use an ensure block to guarantee that the hook will be invoked.  This is possible because VCR wraps the entire request for these library hooks.

Ensure excon retries the right number of times.Previously, when we were recording a cassette, the excon request being tested had a retry count, and for each of those, our hook would make a real request that was also retried that many times.

Ensure excon status errors are handled properly.When you make an excon request with the :expects option, it will raise a subclass of Excon::Errors::HTTPStatusError if the response is not the expected status code.  We were manually re-raising this error before, but the excon code up the call stack* rescues all errors and raises an Excon::Errors::SocketError.  This caused the error class to be different then what it would have been otherwise.  Instead, we want to return the raw response (i.e. no expects error), and we let excon transform this in to a status error.nn* https://github.com/geemus/excon/blob/v0.9.5/lib/excon/connection.rb#L225-232

Work around bug in WebMock's em-http-request adapter.When the :redirects option is used with em-http-request,nWebMock's after_request hook gets invoked twice for ansingle request. It appears to be doing it one for the originalnrequest and once for the following redirect request. However,nthe second time it does not actually have the new URL, and,nfurthermore, the globally_stub_request hook is only invokednonce. As a result, the @__typed_vcr_request ivar has alreadynbeen removed, and we were getting nil on the second after_requestnhook invocation.nnOur fix is to make our WebMock library hook tolerant of then@__typed_vcr_request hook not being present. Some thingsn(such as filtering an after_http_request hook based on requestntype) will not work properly but the main VCR functionality cannwork this way.nnCloses #171.

It turns out it can trivially be re-used. I've refactored the implementation tonno longer assume that. Fix excon so real requests are made with a connection constructed with same args.I got this warning from VCR on some tests using fog/excon to download a file from S3 over SSL:nnWARNING: VCR could not extract a response from Excon error (#<OpenSSL::SSL::SSLError: hostname does not match the server certificate>)nnI discovered that the SSL cert verification for a real request w/o VCR was made againstn`s3.amazonaws.com`, while the verification for the request being recorded by VCR was madenagainst `<bucket_name>.s3.amazonaws.com`. The difference is due to the fact that fognconstructs an Excon::Connection instance with a URI of `s3.amazonaws.com`, then makes anrequest with a :host param set to the FQDN. Before this commit, VCR made the realnrequest by constructing a new Excon::Connection instance with the URI set to the fullnURI, and it caused the SSL cert verification failure.nnThis fixes it by ensuring the real request connection instance is constructed withnthe same args as the original connection instance.

Ensure Typhoeus' effective_url is recorded/played back properly.When a request was made with the `followlocation: true`noption and the response was a redirect, `effective_url`nwas being set to the wrong value on playback.nnTyphoeus passes this option to libcurl, and the redirectnis followed in native curl code, rather than in rubyland;nas a result we cannot record both the redirect responsenand the followed responseu00e2u0080u00a6we just get the final followednresponse. We were setting `effective_url` to the request urlnbut typhoeus internally sets it to the final url (afternall the redirects).  So, to play it back properly we havento record that value.  I've added `adapter_metadata`nas a generic place to store adapter-specific metadata valuesnthat need to be recorded.nnFixes #293.n

travis: cache bundle across jobsInstalling dependencies via Bundler can make up a large portion ofnthe build duration. Caching the bundle between builds drasticallynreduces the time a build takes to run.nnCaching does not become effective until this commit is mergednto master. At that point, `bundle install` on travis takesn20-30 seconds instead of several minutes. If a branch modifiesnthe gemspec, then that branch starts with the cache but stillnuses the updated gemspec.nnIn my experience with travis-ci bundler cache, only the defaultnbranch *writes* the cache. All other branches merely *read*.nnhttp://about.travis-ci.org/docs/user/caching/n

Mitigate threading issues on the HTTP interactions list (#690)One VCR threading issue is that when multiple request come across in separate threads, the list interactions is not synchronized, causing errors due to loss of tracking of the un/used interactions.rnrnThis commit places two mutexes in the core sections of contention:rnrn- the first instantiation of HTTPInteractionList, which without mutex, yields to a second instance overwriting the first (reference)rn- the transfer of a given request from the unused interactions list to the used one, and other problemsrnrnPlease note that this commit is not intended to make VCR thread safe in the absolute sense, but it intends to mitigate (possibly not solve) one specific threading problem experienced by multiple users.rnrnCloses #200, depending on the maintaners intention towards VCR thread-safety.

Fix turning off VCR not working when server thread already startu00e2u0080u00a6 (#764)When VCR is first used in the main (test) thread, it initializes arncontext, holding the status of whether VCR is turned off. When anotherrnthread is started (ie. app server), VCR initializes a context there byrnduplicating the main thread's context and linking to the main thread'srncontext.rnrnIf you turned off VCR in the main thread after it's context wasrnduplicated to an additional thread, the additional thread wouldn't seernthe new turned off status (since it was only on the linked context), sornit'd fail thinking VCR was still turned on but no cassette was insertedrnwhen a request was made.rnrnNow we check both the current thread's context, and the linked (main)rnthread's context to see if VCR is turned off, to ensure an app serverrnthread can see when VCR is turned off on the main thread.rnrnThis was most noticeable in Capybara tests with a JS driver where thernapp server thread was started once upon the first spec needing it, thusrnduplicating the main thread's context then, but if later specs turnedrnoff VCR, the app server thread never had it's context updated to reflectrnthat, nor did it check the main thread's context to see if VCR wasrnturned off there.rnrnCo-authored-by: Kurtis Rainbolt-Greene <kurtis@rainbolt-greene.online>rnCo-authored-by: Olle Jonsson <olle.jonsson@gmail.com>rn
